{{Infobox artist | name = Ilit Azoulay | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1972}} | birth_place = [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]] | nationality = [[Israel]]i | field = [[photography]] | training = [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] | movement = [[Israeli art]] | works = | patrons = | awards = Les Rencontres d'Arles Discovery Award }}
'''Ilit Azoulay''' (born 1972) is an Israeli artist. She is best known for panoramic [[Photomontage|photo montages]], depicting arrangements of different objects and materials she has collected from demolished buildings around the southern districts of [[Tel Aviv]]. She visited the buildings before demolition, exploring their rooms and examining their walls. After the demolition, Azoulay returned, searching through the remains and gathering pieces of them. In the studio, she sorted and cataloged the findings. Then photographs are made separately and used for collage preparation.
== Biography == Azoulay was born in the [[Jaffa]] district of [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]]. She received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]] from the [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] in [[Jerusalem]] in 1998 and [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] of [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] in Tel Aviv in 2010. She lives and works in Tel Aviv.
She had solo exhibitions in [[Andrea Meislin Gallery]] in New York and [[Herzliya Museum of Contemporary Art]] as well as [[Braverman Gallery]], Tel Aviv.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/life/culture/why-the-curator-came-down-to-earth-1.467015|title=Why the Curator Came Down to Earth|date=27 September 2012|publisher=|via=Haaretz}}</ref> She also participated in numerous group exhibitions around the world. She is currently a resident at the [[Kunst-Werke Institute for Contemporary Art]] in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/news-in-brief/news-in-brief-1.483990|title=News in Brief|date=11 December 2012|publisher=|via=Haaretz}}</ref> She has works in permanent collections of museums as well as in private collections in Israel and abroad.
== Exhibitions == * ''The Keys'', Andrea Meislin Gallery, New York, 2011.{{cn|date=June 2018}} * ''Room #8'', Andrea Meislin Gallery, New York, 2013.{{cn|date=June 2018}} * ''Linguistic Turn'', Bravernman Gallery, Tel Aviv, Israel, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravermangallery.com/exhibitions/ilit-azoulay-linguistic-turn-bakery-tommy-hartung-anna/ |title=Linguistic Turn |publisher=Braverman Gallery |date= |accessdate=2018-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravermangallery.com/press/ilit-azoulays-solo-exhibition-linguistic-turn-including-an-interview-with-her-on-galeria-haaretz/|title=Ilit Azoulay’s solo exhibition “Linguistic Turn” including an interview with her on Galeria, Ha’aretz - Braverman Gallery|website=bravermangallery.com}}</ref> * ''Public Installation'', [[Museum of Contemporary Canadian Art]], Toronto, Canada, 2013. * ''Implicit Manifestation'', [[Herzliya Museum of Contemporary Art]], Herzliya, Israel, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.herzliyamuseum.co.il/english/september-2014/implicit-manifestation/about# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-05-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518072318/http://www.herzliyamuseum.co.il/english/september-2014/implicit-manifestation/about# |archive-date=2015-05-18 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> * ''Shifting Degrees of Certainty'', [[Kunst-Werke Institute for Contemporary Art]], Berlin, 2014. * ''[[Rencontres d'Arles]] Discovery Award'', Arles, France, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjp-online.com/2014/07/dispatches-from-arles-2014-the-highs-and-lows/|title=Dispatches from Arles 2014: the highs and lows – British Journal of Photography|website=www.bjp-online.com}}</ref>
