[[File:A.Bert - Isaac de Camondo.jpg|thumb|Photograph of Comte Isaac de Camondo circa 1890]] Comte '''Isaac de Camondo''' (born 3 July 1851 in [[Constantinople]]; died 7 April 1911 in [[Paris]]) was a member of the [[House of Camondo]] noted primarily as an art collector<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=B6JTCCBSZuoC&q=camondo#v=snippet&q=camondo&f=false Cézanne to Picasso edited by Rebecca A. Rabinow, Douglas W. Druick, and Maryline Assante di Panzillo]</ref> with a noteworrthy interest in the then "avant-garde" artists of the [[Impressionism|Impressionist]]<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=pZAp3SWO-TYC&pg=PA191&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false Jewish Icons by Richard I. Cohen, pg 191]</ref> and [[Post-Impressionism|Post-Impressionist]] movements. He bequeathed his collection to [[The Louvre]] in 1908.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=BngwOaFvEecC&pg=PA159&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false André Salmon on French Modern Art by André Salmon]</ref> He worked as a banker<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ItqhNQusviAC&pg=PA426&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false International Banking 1870-1914 edited by Rondo Cameron William Rand, pg 426]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HrSJ4STXbuAC&pg=PT208&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false The New Bibliopolis] by [[Willa Z. Silverman]], pg 208</ref> and was an amateur composer.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wNcqAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA104&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false The Monthly Musical Record, Volume 36, pg 104]</ref>
